All in all, I like it more than learner's dicts from Pearson and Oxford, because it (1) has comparative and superlative forms of adjectives and ADVERBS, (2) example sentences are easy to understand for a learner, (3) it shows which meaning is countable and which uncountable (unlike Pearson and Oxford where you need to guess) and (4) definitions are much more clear than the competion's (written without difficult words, with synonims, so that you can understand the difference between meanings)

Although some users have complained that the Merriam-Webster's Learners dictionary is inferior or the same as the Merriam-Websters Advanced dictionary, I'd like to set the record straight by pointing out that the difference lies in the way that the entries are explained. Using fewer, simpler and clear words to explain meanings. However, my disappointment goes to the sluggishness of the app, which in some cases made me turn to another dictionary to find the meaning of a certain word, despite being installed on two different, 2017, cutting-edge smartphones.

üëéüò§  This appears to be an unfinished-half-assed app. It has a lot of issues, such as scrolling and page transition animation hiccups, which are really frustrating. Also the obvious lack of useful contents, such as illustrations and sample sentences, clearly makes this buggy dictionary a total money rip-off! I hope that the developers will act on this known problems as soon as possible to improve this potentially great learning tool.  Not recommended until it's completely fixed!üëéüò§
